#   GET-004: `be://` path â†’ store resolution (userinfo home, `.be` default, non-hidden `*.be`, worktree)

[GET-003] fixed the empty-path case; this ticket specifies the *full `be://` pathâ†’store resolution* (authoritative semantics from the user). For `be://[user@]host[/path]`: the *userinfo selects the peer home* (`be://gritzko@localhost` â†’ `/home/gritzko`, default = the ssh-login user); an *empty path* denotes that home's hidden default store `<home>/.be` (GET-003); a *non-empty path is HOME-relative* with one uniform rule â€” a path *ending in `.be` is the store itself* (`be://localhost/store.be` â†’ `$HOME/store.be`, the `*.git` analogue), and *any other path gets `/.be` appended* (`be://localhost/src/beagle` â†’ `$HOME/src/beagle/.be`), where that `.be` resolves *whether it is a directory (a store) or a file (a worktree pointer) â€” it does not matter which*. Today keeper resolves a pathless `?/proj` via a cwd walk-up from the login HOME to `<home>/.be` (GET-003) and a worktree/pathful form already negotiates (`be://localhost/beagle?`), but the explicit `<path>/.be` append, the `*.be` named-store form, and the `user@` â†’ home selection are unspecified/unverified. See [GET], [URI], [blog/uris.mkd], [CLAUDE].

##  Issues
The path slot of a `be://` URL means "which store on the peer", but only two of the four cases are wired.

 -  `be://[user@]host` (empty path) â†’ `<home>/.be`, where `<home>` is the userinfo user's home (`gritzko@` â†’ `/home/gritzko`), default = ssh-login user. GET-003 handles the login-user default; the explicit `user@` selection is untested.
 -  `be://host/<name>.be` â†’ `<home>/<name>.be`, a *non-hidden* store dir named in the path (HOME-relative). Keeper must recognize a `*.be` path as a store (not a worktree) â€” the `*.git` analogue. Currently unverified.
 -  `be://host/<worktree>` â†’ the worktree's repo, resolved through its `.be`. Confirm this already works (the pathful `be://localhost/beagle?` form negotiates) and is HOME-relative.
 -  Disambiguation rule on the server: how keeper decides store-vs-worktree for a given path â€” `*.be` suffix â‡’ store; else a dir containing a `.be` â‡’ worktree. Must be explicit and tested.
 -  HOME-relative convention already exists client-side (`keeper/WIRECLI.c:231-237` strips the leading `/`); the server resolves the rest relative to the login HOME.

